    <note>Tan(4) Gu [18486] In 1094, he criticized the dismissal of Lu(9) Dafang [1327], Su(1) Che [1493] and Fan(2) Chunren [559] and the employment of Zhang(2) Dun [333], Zeng(1) Zhao [7072] and Cai(1) Bian [8131]. When Cai(1) Jing [1649] took over the government, Gu was purged, included in the 1102 purge as a Yuanfu coalition member, and never again employed. According to Cao(1) Yanyue's [10840] funerary inscription for Tan(4) Huan [18501], the Tan(4) were a great lineage (wangzu) of Chizhou, Jiande (modern Zhide) county. With the exception of Gu and Mengxiang [18493], the generational names follow logically--Zong+x, and single character mingzi with radical 9. I am going to treat Gu as lineage cousin of a Tan(4) A, [18532] who will be the uncle of the Zong+x and granduncle of the Tan(4), who use radical 9 as the generational inidicator in their mingzi. Mengxiang is identified as Gu's lineage kin +5. Anhui TZ, 154.9a. CBD, 5, 4130.</note>
